segments.text: She awoke long before the birds, outside darkness still prevailed.
Something bothered her that morning, an inexplicable restlessness.
She lay on the mattress, eyes wide open, staring into the dark nothingness that surrounded her.
Ben-Ben slept beside her, his small leg on her stomach, one hand seemingly shielding his face.
It was hard to see much in the surrounding darkness, yet she found herself staring into that nothingness, trying to understand what had woken her.
She was aware she felt something tangible, some worry mixed with anxiety she couldn't comprehend.
Beyond the intense longing for Dan and the uncertainty that accompanied her days, she proceeded quietly, calmly.
That was her nature and the way she wished to raise her son.
And now, suddenly, as if some warning bell rang inside her, urging her to open her eyes even before dawn.
She lay like that for a long time, staring.
Until suddenly, she noticed the first light of morning filtering through the blinds, slowly bringing the new day into her room.
It was still very early.
She already heard the birds chirping and thought to herself with a smile.
Don't brag, this morning I beat you."
But the smile quickly faded from her face, and the same worry mixed with anxiety spread through her again.
She recognized something different in the bird's chirping, as if the sparrows were crying.
Perhaps they were trying to warn in their way of a day that brought something bad.
Each time she was amazed when she realized the sparrows were crying, she was already familiar with that unique and so different chirping.
If only I could chirp back to them so they wouldn't worry so much.
After all, there's always a new day tomorrow, and who knows it better than me.
The Sparrows had become her seismograph for daily affairs and the future to come.
And she immediately went on alert.
What will be?
What will happen?
Something about the crying sparrows with that anxious restlessness enveloping her made her straighten up as if to stand guard.
But then Ben Ben opened his eyes and smiled at her, a big smile that instantly quieted the worry that spread within her.
The next two hours she spent in her usual morning routine, washing, dressing Ben Ben and preparing breakfast for the both of them.
She opened the glass doors overlooking the garden, and a light breeze blew in.
Ru-ha, called Ben-Ben.
She laughed.
Yes, wind, say ro-o-cha.
She instructed him.
Ru-cha, he repeated, unable to correctly pronounce those words ending in cha from the few words he already knew.
He would say, Appleha, Ruha, and it was so sweet.
She found herself reciting to him.
Wind, wind, wind, wind, and Apple fell in the grove.
It fell from the treetop.
It fell and went boom.
Ben, Ben called and clapped his hands and they both laughed.
When she was with him, something calmed within her.
momentarily forgetful of the inner alarm that woke her, forgetful of the crying sparrows.
In her small hotel, there were eight tenants at the time, occupying most of the ten rooms meant for rent.
Josuke, from the semi-trailer, two veterinary doctors, a magistrate judge, a trainee lawyer doing his internship with Joseph's close friend.
And a strange English-speaking couple in their fifties.
It seemed the woman was recovering from some illness.
Every morning her husband would take a tray of breakfast to their room.
There was also an older and well-known singer who composed and wrote his own songs, then working on new songs for his album.
He was the only one there during the day.
As he woke up late, he would be content with black coffee at his awakening and sometimes with something light.
Until dinner, per his request, he arrived at the pink house over ten years ago, fleeing there whenever the creative spirit overtook him.
Joseph always left him a key even at night, and he would close the windows tight, sit at the piano, and work at night, as did she.
Josuke, the vets and the judge, would leave early in the morning, and she only saw them in the early evening hours.
They returned straight to their rooms, washed off, and came for dinner, sometimes altogether.
Sometimes individually.
Oddly enough, Josuke from the semi-trailer became very friendly with Jacob, the magistrate judge.
This.

Rugged and large driver, with a sole tender as a bird's, found common ground with Jacob the judge, small statured, intelligent, with beautiful and quiet language like his good eyes, often sharing meals together, enjoying each other's company.
The two veterinarians were relatively new, having moved from the north for a while after Danny, her vet, went abroad.
He was so sorry it happened precisely when she needed him most before Ben Ben's birth.
These two vets were young and novices in their field.
One of them studied in Belgium and when he realized she lived alone, he tried to court her.
It embarrassed her a bit.
She had forgotten what courting was.
Yosuke, noticing this, spun him some yarn about her husband being on a mission abroad, not even knowing how accurate he was and that any day now he'd return.
Only then did the fellow calm down.
Every day, she made sure to cook something else.
Fresh homemade food, Lucy's food, as she learned from years of observation, and everyone was very satisfied.
Some went to their rooms right after dinner.
Some stayed in the bar or on the sofa corner.
Sometimes they drank a glass of beer.
Sometimes something a bit stronger.
Shimon the singer drank a little more than others.
And the night before, after a few drinks, when he was in good spirits, he sat at the piano and began to sing for them with his deep bass voice.
melting her heart and seemingly theirs as well.
The judge joined him with the lyrics of the songs and revealed himself to have a deep and charming voice.
She didn't move from the piano, utterly savoring the wonders of the music filling the walls of her pink house.

After everyone dispersed, she finished tidying up, took up the sleeping Ben-Ben from his mattress in the kitchen entrance, wished the singer a good night, and left him by the piano to create his melodies.
In the morning she found a note on the piano lid, thanks for a productive night, took three more glasses of whiskey, note them on my bill.
When the hotel was filled with tenants, she was happy.
but there were days when no one came, and she would clean and polish, moving from room to room, changing sheets and towels, and no one came.
She would garden with all her might, bending between the silver baskets and pansies, and no one came.
Then she would enter the kitchen to cook a dish that would spread aromas everywhere, and no one came.
Finally, she would sit at the piano, hoping its sounds would be heard far and wide, and still no one came.
She was unknowingly calling them with the aroma of the cooking and the sound of the piano.
To come and fill her small hotel and keep her company, knowing a hotel cannot sit in solitude, a hotel needs people.
When two, sometimes three days passed and no one came, she felt her body become slightly rigid as if her movements were losing flexibility and even her fingers on the piano felt less nimble.
She would shrink into herself more and more.
She found herself increasingly nestled in the corner chair, immersed in a book, into different worlds, sometimes even falling asleep with the book resting on her chest.

She knew how to fill her days, both with her tasks around maintaining the hotel and her personal whims, such as the books she devoured, the music she listened to, her comforting piano, and the letters she wrote with her small, beautiful handwriting, filling pages densely for her beloved cousin still in the Army.
for the friend who shared the school bench with her, for Danny who called her Annabelle Lee because she was crazy about Edgar Allan Poe and recited his poem in its entirety.
She wrote about her thoughts, her plans, not touching on the difficulties, not recounting the burdensome things, embellishing the picture as she imagined it, painting it pink as usual.
But with all this together, there remained time to wait for those who would come.
She was a master at being alone, but she knew one couldn't be alone all the time.

Deep in her heart, she was a people person, loved them, loved to ponder over the new folks, discern the essence of one person from another, able to identify tights from years of observation since she was a child.
Joseph used to say, I have a girl with.
Antennis, the truth was, she simply was attentive.
They genuinely interested her.
Only Yossi the postman came daily, even when he had no mail for her.
He was used to finishing his delivery round at their place, resting his feet, receiving a cup of tea from Lucy, and sitting for a short chat.
She recognized his longing for her and continued the tradition after Lucy passed away.
Every time he arrived, he would sit in the garden and praise her for continuing to tend to it.
This garden looks wonderful.
For me it's like a quiet blooming paradise, and the live fence around it seems to frame it from the outside world.
She was already used to his effusions.
She always thought it would be better if he wrote poetry instead of distributing what others wrote.
He had an eloquent language and a deep voice, and it was always pleasant to listen to him.
Only his legs hurt from the kilometers he walked daily between the houses of the big neighborhood.
I rest them in the garden of the pink house, he said, and at another time added, I'm sure Lucy looks down and is very proud of you.
She was very touched by his words.
I constantly feel as if she's watching, accompanying me, and I strive to keep her garden blooming so that if she does indeed look down, she won't be sad.
After a little while, Yasi the postman also left and no one came.
Then, just when it seemed to her it had been too long since anyone came.
Suddenly the door swung open, and in the entrance she saw Yoski from the semi-trailer, in all his rugged bigness and warm, large smile, as if reporting for duty to save her from her solitude.
Hello, his voice boomed.
I haven't been down south for a week.
That's why I didn't come.
Did you save my room for me?
Was there something to eat?
And she laughed a carefree laugh in front of him, feeling her body relax, knowing that even one was much more than nothing.
Knowing that as always others would follow him because even if she could be alone, a hotel couldn't.
A hotel needs people.
